{
  "title": "The Hand That Went Up",
  "pages": [
    {
      "pageNumber": 1,
      "text": "Eli sat in the third row, second seat from the window, where the morning light came in sideways and made the dust float like tiny planets. He was the kind of boy who already knew the answer while everyone else was still reading the question. Not because he tried to be first. It just happened, the way breathing happened — quietly, without deciding to."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 2,
      "text": "Knowing things felt safe to Eli. Like solid ground under his feet. Like a wall at his back. As long as he knew the answer — the whole answer, all the way to the end — he was okay. He could sit still. He could breathe. Everything was fine."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 3,
      "text": "It was a Tuesday in late autumn. The classroom was warm and a little too bright, and the air smelled like dry-erase markers. Ms. Vargas turned to the board and began writing a math problem in chunky blue letters. Around Eli, pencils tapped and chairs shifted and someone erased something twice. Eli looked at the numbers and felt something move in his mind — quiet and sure, like a key turning in a lock."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 4,
      "text": "He knew the first step. He was almost certain about the second. But then the third step was just — fog. A wall of gray where the answer should have been. Eli stared at the problem and the fog didn't move. He told himself what he always told himself: if you don't know all of it, you don't know enough. A half-answer was worse than no answer. A half-answer meant everyone would see exactly where you stopped."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 5,
      "text": "\"Who wants to give it a try?\" Ms. Vargas asked, turning around with the marker still in her hand. Eli's hand moved. He hadn't told it to. It lifted a few inches off his desk — just a few, barely anything — and then he saw it happening and pulled it back down and pressed it flat against his leg. His jaw tightened. Too slow. Ms. Vargas was already looking at him. \"I notice a hand,\" she said. \"Eli?\""
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 6,
      "text": "Every sound in the room disappeared. Eli's chest squeezed like someone was sitting on it. He tried to take a breath and the air came in wrong, too shallow, not enough. His face felt hot. Twenty-two kids were looking at him. He thought: I should have kept my hand down. I should have known better. He thought: don't say anything. But his mouth was already opening."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 7,
      "text": "\"You start by grouping the tens,\" Eli said. His voice came out smaller than he wanted. \"And then — and then you carry the one.\" He could feel the first step and the second step leaving his mouth like they were real things, solid things. And then he reached the edge. The fog was right there. He stopped. The pause stretched out wide and awful. His face went hotter. This was it. This was exactly the thing he had been afraid of his whole life."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 8,
      "text": "The room waited. Eli looked at his desk. He thought about saying never mind. He thought about saying sorry. But those words felt like hiding, and something in him — something tired of hiding — pushed a different set of words up instead. \"I don't know what comes next,\" he said. Quietly. Honestly. Just the truth of where he was."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 9,
      "text": "Ms. Vargas didn't make a face. She didn't sigh. She looked at Eli and said, \"Good start. Who wants to go from here?\" That was all. And a hand went up across the room. Marcus. Eli's stomach dropped a little. Marcus always knew everything. Marcus finished tests first. Marcus was the last person Eli wanted to watch get it right."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 10,
      "text": "Marcus started talking. \"So after you carry the one, you've got to regroup the hundreds column, and that means—\" He paused. Eli looked up. Marcus's forehead was scrunched. Marcus chewed the inside of his cheek. \"Wait,\" Marcus said. \"I'm not sure either.\" He said it the same way Eli had said it. Like it was just a fact. Like it wasn't the end of the world. Eli felt something strange and warm move through his chest."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 11,
      "text": "Ms. Vargas wrote something on the board and then stopped and said, \"Hmm. Let me think for a second.\" She looked at the numbers, tilting her head. Then a girl named Priya raised her hand and said she thought she saw it, and she added the next piece, and then another kid added something after that, and slowly, in small pieces, the problem came apart and came back together again."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 12,
      "text": "The answer went up on the board in pieces. Eli's piece was there, at the start. Marcus's piece was in the middle. Priya's piece was near the end. Eli looked at the finished numbers and couldn't tell where one part stopped and the next part started. It was just the answer. All of it together, from all of them. He looked at it for a long moment. Something in his chest shifted, the way a drawer slides closed when you finally push it right."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 13,
      "text": "When the bell rang and everyone started moving, Eli pulled on his backpack and walked out into the hallway. His chest was still a little tight. His face still felt warm. He was not fixed. He knew that. Tomorrow there would be another problem on the board and he would probably feel the same thing in the same place in his chest, that squeezing, that wanting to disappear."
    },
    {
      "pageNumber": 14,
      "text": "But walking down the hallway, Eli looked at his hand. The one that had gone up halfway. The one he had pulled back. The one that had ended up going all the way — not raised, exactly, but speaking, which was harder. He turned it over and looked at it like it was something he was still figuring out. It did something today, he thought. It did something today."
    }
  ]
}
